document.title: Woodbridge High School Biology I Learning Targets

3392FCD48F9A48E4A3441D2417CB225E.description: I can design, evaluate, and refine a solution for reducing the negative effects of human activity on a Virginia watershed or ecosystem.

1052AC0D19C94D538C3C421551B0947F.description: I can provide examples to illustrate and explain how habitat destruction, pollution, introduction of invasive species, overexploitation, and climate change can disrupt an ecosystem and threaten the survival of species.

1F15D4CEFD5E49D9867367443234BB61.description: I can describe the characteristics of a climax community.

E7D1882E4EDB4B3696DBEC0C1E0FF419.description: I can identify factors leading to primary and secondary succession.

051E0124D16B44A2937E0DE9880546F0.description: I can describe the patterns of succession found in aquatic and terrestrial ecosystems of Virginia.

FD87240901024673B5B5E1DDE2175782.description: I can recognize and understand the cause-and-effect relationship between changes in the abiotic and biotic conditions in an ecosystem and succession.

4465A6D4F83F49C18A8603AD09CC0713.description: I can evaluate claims, evidence, and reasoning that the complex interactions in ecosystems maintain relatively consistent numbers and types of organisms in stable conditions, but changing conditions may result in a new ecosystem

3DC61F0A41714A2CA2A645D6AE758F60.description: I can develop a model to illustrate the role of photosynthesis and cellular respiration in the cycling of carbon among the biosphere, atmosphere, hydrosphere, and geosphere

A056650FFEC74E91B358D606584B85EE.description:
I can interpret how the flow of energy occurs between trophic levels in all ecosystems in a:  

food chain 
food web 
pyramid of energy 
pyramid of biomass

9A973D7272A14CF9BF227B86DBF4D40B.description: I can graph and interpret a population growth curve and identify the carrying capacity of the population.

7D7ADCADB4BB4529879B421FEF00E7B1.description: I can make predictions about changes that could occur in population numbers as the result of population interactions.

D5BC0DF2D8434663B3D62D0F2BEE0A2A.description: I can use mathematical representations such as charts, graphs, histograms, and population change data, to support explanations of factors that affect carrying capacity of ecosystems.

9BA89A8C404649B78FA30E8B85F89F0F.description: I can use evidence from scientific literature and research to support a claim on the use or misuse of vaccines or antibiotics

F46C0CF87A6441D3BB810AD5FB108099.description: I can describe how germ theory exemplifies the nature of science as supported by evidence.

F92250C0BFEC47E0AAA3422F7B5DA8A6.description: I can provide an evidence-based explanation that connects the germ theory to the nature of science, such as describing the effects of Pasteur’s and Koch’s experiments on the understanding of disease transmission.

34AE3DD4AEE246099120AC61FC9E2C7E.description: I can examine effects of bacteria on human health.

0F108A2C2350458EA937A2193CD272F9.description: I can compare a virus and a bacterium in relation to genetic material and reproduction.

575011CB0AC24660AD7A57FBF9BD8EB1.description: I can I can examine effects of viruses on human health.

2BB0DF4CC3404D9EABD4ADEEBB5CE931.description: I can use evidence to support the viruses as nonliving.

8A4EAE31E2C54CCAB881AD4407EE7997.description: I can explain in simple terms how viruses infect host organisms.

42C998C44D8B4180AEDE83A17A8388F7.description: I can apply classification criteria to categorize examples of organisms as representatives of the six kingdoms: archaebacteria, eubacteria, protista, fungi, plantae, and animalia.

0869E6DEAA564C5D82ABFA592AEAD381.description: I can apply classification criteria to categorize examples of organisms as representatives of the three domains: Archaea, Bacteria, and Eukarya.

3804E0C3449E463D987AB331363D4701.description: I can recognize similarities in embryonic stages in diverse organisms in the animal kingdom, from zygote through embryo, and infer relationships.

03154BB41EBB43579DC2ED97697B4B45.description: I can interpret a cladogram or phylogenetic tree to make inferences about relationships.

33C35AACA236424798060CF7809D4CCB.description: I can analyze and interpret data for patterns in the fossil record that document the existence, diversity, extinction, and change of life forms throughout the history of life on Earth (under the assumption that natural laws operate today as in the past).

5F53EC3C8D5346649AA4BE99649C8489.description: I can compare structural characteristics of an extinct organism, as evidenced by its fossil record, with present, familiar organisms.

A3E5D8F8933242BEAEC1C6272A4D0D23.description: I can recognize new attributes (physical and chemical) that affect the taxonomic group into which an organism is (or was) placed (BIO.6 f).

4CF7A377429A4DB5BEDC6D5BFA3C7D9A.description: I can recognize similarities in embryonic stages in diverse organisms in the animal kingdom, from zygote through embryo, and infer relationships (BIO.6 c)

9FAFDAF7DC6243B8AFFEA41B88EB5942.description: I can recognize scientific names as part of a binomial nomenclature (BIO.6 a)

085F46B9F35848CDA74DA9FB18B8885B.description: I can arrange organisms in a hierarchy according to similarities and differences in structural and biochemical characteristics (BIO.6 a)

6FBFD6BC12054865BA51785B26D0AEE8.description: I can construct an explanation for the anatomical similarities and differences among modern organisms and between modern and fossil organisms to infer evolutionary relationships.

1177E88322174FFD9575E7C531F233E1.description: I can explain how natural selection led to changes in gene frequency in populations over time.

0E56BDBD93E2473EA3ED6A3E3DE14EF3.description: I can provide evidence to support the argument that variations for a given trait within a population may be helpful or harmful to the survival of a population when environmental pressures arise.

0D35906E3F584E6A9726766B7794F612.description: I can make and defend a claim based on evidence from scientific literature that inheritable genetic variations may result from new genetic combinations through meiosis.

583BFB4D7CAD45DCABA1558559D028E5.description: I can compare the process of mitosis and meiosis and determine which conditions are necessary for each process to occur.
